<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<appendix xml:id="app-cell-count-normal-approx">
  <title>Cell Counts and Normal Approximation</title>

  <p>This appendix explains why large cell counts in a contingency table are often treated as approximately normal. The main idea is simple: a count is a sum of many 0-or-1 indicators. This gives the normal approximation through the central limit theorem. A closely related Poisson approximation explains why the denominator <m>\sqrt{E_{ij}}</m> appears in the Pearson chi-square statistic.</p>

  <section xml:id="sec-cell-count-one-cell">
    <title>Start with One Cell</title>

    <p>Fix one cell <m>(i,j)</m> in a two-way table. For each observation <m>k=1,\ldots,n</m>, define</p>

    <me>
      X_k=
      \begin{cases}
      1, &amp; \text{if observation }k\text{ falls in cell }(i,j),\\
      0, &amp; \text{otherwise.}
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>Then the observed <term>cell count<idx><h>contingency tables</h><h>cell count</h></idx></term> is</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}=X_1+X_2+\cdots+X_n.
    </me>

    <p>So <m>O_{ij}</m> is a sum of many Bernoulli random variables. If the true probability of falling in cell <m>(i,j)</m> is <m>p_{ij}</m>, then</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}\sim B(n,p_{ij}).
    </me>

    <p>Therefore</p>

    <me>
      E(O_{ij})=np_{ij}
    </me>

    <p>and</p>

    <me>
      \operatorname{Var}(O_{ij})=np_{ij}(1-p_{ij}).
    </me>

    <p>By the <term>central limit theorem<idx><h>theorems</h><h>central limit theorem</h></idx></term>, for large <m>n</m>,</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}\approx
      N\left(np_{ij},\sqrt{np_{ij}(1-p_{ij})}\right).
    </me>

    <p>Here <m>N(\mu,\sigma)</m> means a normal distribution with mean <m>\mu</m> and standard deviation <m>\sigma</m>.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cell-count-expected-counts">
    <title>Expected Counts Under Independence</title>

    <p>In a test of independence, the null hypothesis says that the row and column variables are independent. In probability language,</p>

    <me>
      p_{ij}=p_{i\cdot}p_{\cdot j}.
    </me>

    <p>The expected count under independence is therefore</p>

    <me>
      E_{ij}=np_{i\cdot}p_{\cdot j}.
    </me>

    <p>Since the row and column probabilities are usually unknown, we estimate them from the table. That gives the familiar formula</p>

    <me>
      E_{ij}
      =
      \frac{(\text{row }i\text{ total})(\text{column }j\text{ total})}
      {\text{grand total}}.
    </me>

    <p>At this point, a useful first approximation is that <m>O_{ij}</m> is centered near <m>E_{ij}</m> and is roughly normal when the expected count is large enough.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cell-count-poisson-approx">
    <title>The Square Root Scaling</title>

    <p>For a binomial cell count, the exact standard deviation is</p>

    <me>
      \sqrt{np_{ij}(1-p_{ij})}.
    </me>

    <p>If <m>E_{ij}=np_{ij}</m>, this is</p>

    <me>
      \sqrt{E_{ij}(1-p_{ij})}.
    </me>

    <p>So the statement</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}\approx N(E_{ij},\sqrt{E_{ij}})
    </me>

    <p>is not literally exact for one cell in a fixed-total multinomial table. The cleaner reason for the denominator <m>\sqrt{E_{ij}}</m> comes from a <term>Poisson approximation<idx><h>distributions</h><h>Poisson approximation</h></idx></term>.</p>

    <p>If <m>Y\sim\operatorname{Poisson}(\lambda)</m>, then</p>

    <me>
      E(Y)=\lambda,
      \qquad
      \operatorname{Var}(Y)=\lambda.
    </me>

    <p>For large <m>\lambda</m>, a Poisson random variable is approximately normal:</p>

    <me>
      Y\approx N(\lambda,\sqrt{\lambda}).
    </me>

    <p>Thus, if a cell count is modeled approximately as</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}\sim\operatorname{Poisson}(E_{ij}),
    </me>

    <p>then</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}\approx N(E_{ij},\sqrt{E_{ij}}),
    </me>

    <p>and the quantity</p>

    <me>
      \frac{O_{ij}-E_{ij}}{\sqrt{E_{ij}}}
    </me>

    <p>is approximately standard normal.</p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cell-count-caveat">
    <title>The Important Caveat</title>

    <p>In an actual fixed-total contingency table, the cell counts are not independent. They are constrained by the grand total, and when we estimate expected counts from the row and column totals, the entries are tied together even more.</p>

    <p>So it is not quite right to say that every Pearson residual</p>

    <me>
      \frac{O_{ij}-E_{ij}}{\sqrt{E_{ij}}}
    </me>

    <p>is individually an independent standard normal random variable. The better statement is this:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Cell-count errors are approximately normal for large samples.</p></li>
      <li><p>The Pearson chi-square statistic is a squared, scaled measure of those errors.</p></li>
      <li><p>The row and column constraints remove some directions of variation.</p></li>
      <li><p>After those constraints are accounted for, only <m>(r-1)(c-1)</m> independent directions of departure from independence remain.</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>That is why, under the null hypothesis of independence and with expected counts large enough,</p>

    <me>
      \sum_{i=1}^r\sum_{j=1}^c
      \frac{(O_{ij}-E_{ij})^2}{E_{ij}}
      \approx
      \chi^2[(r-1)(c-1)].
    </me>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cell-count-bottom-line">
    <title>Bottom Line</title>

    <p>It is reasonable to view <m>O_{ij}</m> as roughly normal because it is a large count, meaning a sum of many Bernoulli indicators. The simplified approximation</p>

    <me>
      O_{ij}\approx N(E_{ij},\sqrt{E_{ij}})
    </me>

    <p>comes from the Poisson-count picture. For a fixed-total contingency table this is only a heuristic cell-by-cell statement, but it gives the right intuition for why the Pearson statistic is chi-square after the row and column constraints are taken into account.</p>
  </section>
</appendix>
